english:
  title: A Record of the No-Hiding Hermitage
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The abbot of Mount Songsan's Sunga Temple at Tiantai is a worthy descendant of the Yi clan of Jeonui. Born into an official family, he renounced the world, studied the Buddha's way at Caoxi, and became foremost among the Four Selections. Yet he abandoned even this, withdrawing deep into the mountains to seek the very essence of Buddhism in the ground of the mind. Before completing this quest, his father compelled him to sit for the monastic examination. He passed and was placed at Tiantai, receiving the highest rank and attaining samadhi in the realm of boundless meaning.

    When the flames of war came in the year Xinxin, and temples lay in ashes, the master sheltered his parents in flight, remaining as calm as if within his own home. His parents rejoiced greatly, and all who heard of it marveled at his character. When his parents passed away one after another, he wailed at their coffins and kept vigil beside their tomb for three years—a devotion that even among our Confucian scholars of true commitment few could match. Surely the master possessed something that set him apart from ordinary people.

    ChuanNing County was his mother's home, blessed with beautiful mountains and waters, abundant harvests. It was not like some steep and remote refuge where one gnaws bark and dwells among clouds and mist, severed from the world. Yet the place proved secluded, and few ventured there. Thus could his intentions be discerned.

    Fortunately, when the master of Dongtaing traveled south, they met and composed verses together, and the days seemed too few. There he dwells—in the No-Hiding Hermitage. Dongtaing, having come to love the man and delight in the plums, bamboo, water, and stones that graced his dwelling, cannot forget it to this day. He has asked me to inscribe this account, that his yearning might find expression.

    I said: The meaning behind naming a hermitage escapes me. Yet our Master once said, "My disciples, I hide nothing from you"—a truth I have striven toward all my life but never fully reached. The master here follows a different path, so such words do not apply to him. Yet the master is no ordinary monastic. He has served his parents with filial devotion, he cherishes virtue—thus should we scholars draw him near rather than dismiss him merely for following another teaching.

    Alas, how many in this world wear shameless faces while concealing their true deeds—such is the nature of hiding. But the master shines with perfect transparency, unmarred by even the finest dust of deception. Thus "No-Hiding" is no empty name.

    Observe: within the hermitage dwells a man—those who meet him see his very heart laid bare. Without stands a mountain, luminous; a stream, crystalline. This is the realm where not a grain of dust can settle. Man and landscape—both vast, both luminous, stretching across the ten directions horizontally, penetrating the three times vertically. Who needs seek the master of this place?

    I have long been ill and dream of wandering the mountains and streams to ease my heart's ancient longing. Might the No-Hiding Hermitage grant me one night's rest? I submit this record as my request.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Four Selections (四選) refers to monastic rankings in Buddhist examinations of the era.
  - key: ''
    value: Xinxin year (辛丑) likely refers to conflicts during the Yuan-Ming transition (1361).
  - key: ''
    value: The master of Dongtaing represents Lee Saek himself, as he is addressing this figure in the text.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Confucius saying 'I hide nothing' (無隱) provides the etymological and philosophical foundation for the hermitage's name.
